content: Your privacy policy is not ok. Having your sole discretion to use the recorded conversations for "protection" or amend the policy is just not ok for mental health tracker - the entries made here are even more personal and sensitive than those in a private diary. It's useful to have a way to track moods and prompts to consider what you're thinking about but the cbt focus is not always helpful. For instance, grief after a death is something to be accepted, not challenged. I think it would be a much better app if you could select more easily whether you want help with self compassion during stressful parts of life or whether you want to challenge your thoughts.

This is another in a long list of examples of software retreading old territory by using the buzzword "AI." As far as I can tell, Youper does nothing useful with anything you write, instead just leading you down a decision tree of shallow self-reflections that deprives the user of autonomy and will be obvious to anyone who's done CBT work in the past. A simple mood tracking app that lets you correlate moods and triggers would probably produce more valuable data for most folks.

Amazing. One question: can I recommend this to my friend who's verging on 
psychotic, unchecked emotions, and has never had a therapy session in her 
life because of parental negligence?
replyContent:
Although Youper helps you take control of your emotional health, it does not replace a medical consultation. 
She can count on Youper to help her monitor whether she's improving or worsening over time, use insights to have more informed conversations with her doctor, and learn more about herself.

Youper's website still has multiple places where it says the mindfulness activities, breathing exercises, mood tracking and etc are "free for life" features. This is not the case. My friend had an anxiety attack after I recommended this app because, unbeknownst to me, sometime recently it it went from "free for life" to a "$10 monthly subscription fee." It literally just told him "Sorry, I can't help you because you didn't pay me."  No response from their facebook or twitter answering my questions, either. After I stupidly gushed about "how nice it was to have someone out there just trying to help people without trying to profit off of them." Stupid me for being naive, I suppose.  There are free apps that do the exact same thing as youper without forcing you to pay $10 a month to have an AI say "Oh I see" and "Interesting" before NOT giving you access to a meditation exercises. Daylio tracks your mood, and all the features are available for free ($10 to remove ads and add more options.) Mindfulness Coach from the VA will walk you through learning mindfulness. And Let's Meditate: Guided Meditation is an ad-free meditation app that doesn't require an account.
